WorkItem.Description:
To reproduce the error:

Run The SimpleSample application.
Click Element1 with the mouse to get focus on the control. Using the up arrow and down arrow keys exclusively for navigation: move down to item "Element 15", move back up to "Element 14".  Expand Element 14 using "+". Collapse Element 14 using "-". Move down to "Element 15". Now attempt to move back up to "Element 14". Element 15 turns Blue and keyboard movement is no longer correct.

Looking into the code, I believe the issue is caused by an incorrect setting inside SelectPreviousFromKey when it calls the static method FindAll. I believe the second parameter in the call should be true to ignore invisible items.

        public void SelectPreviousFromKey()
        {
            List<TreeViewExItem> items = TreeViewElementFinder.FindAll(treeViewEx, -->false<--).ToList();
            TreeViewExItem item = GetFocusedItem();
            item = treeViewEx.GetPreviousItem(item, items);
            if (item == null) return;

            // if ctrl is pressed just focus it, so it can be selected by space. Otherwise select it.
            if (!IsControlKeyDown)
            {
                SelectSingleItem(item);
            }

            FocusHelper.Focus(item);
        }
